text:
I need a way to figure out if subsidy is subtracted or not from the price. I originally thought to refactor `getPackagePrice`, but it's used a bunch of places. Let's instead decompose it so that I can use another function that will give me the same result without suffering from repetition (it's critical that this is done in the same way everywhere).

```ts web/breeze/lib/priceUtils.ts
import { purchaseModelCode } from '@otovo/shared/cloudEnums';
import { PerUnitType } from '@otovo/shared/components/Currency/types';
import { Cloud$FinancingOption } from '@otovo/shared/types/cloudApi';
import {
  Cloud$PurchaseModelCode,
  Cloud$SubsidyType,
} from '@otovo/shared/types/cloudEnums';
import { Otovo$Config } from '@otovo/shared/types/otovoweb';
import { shouldSubtractSubsidyFromLeasingPrice } from '../components/Price/utils';
import { subsidyDisplayEnum } from '../constants';

export const packageHasEvChargerData = (
  selectedFinancingOption: Cloud$FinancingOption,
) => {
  if (!selectedFinancingOption.ev_charger_data) {
    return false;
  }
  return Object.keys(selectedFinancingOption.ev_charger_data || {}).length > 0;
};

export const getEvChargerGrossPrice = (
  selectedFinancingOption: Cloud$FinancingOption,
  unmodified = false,
): number => {
  const { ev_charger_data: evChargerFinancing } = selectedFinancingOption;

  if (!packageHasEvChargerData(selectedFinancingOption)) return 0;

  return unmodified
    ? evChargerFinancing.total_gross_price_unmodified
    : evChargerFinancing.total_gross_price;
};

export const packageHasOtherData = (
  selectedFinancingOption: Cloud$FinancingOption,
) => {
  if (!selectedFinancingOption.other_data) {
    return false;
  }
  return Object.keys(selectedFinancingOption.other_data || {}).length > 0;
};

export const getOtherGrossPrice = (
  selectedFinancingOption: Cloud$FinancingOption,
  unmodified = false,
): number => {
  const { other_data: otherData } = selectedFinancingOption;

  if (!packageHasOtherData(selectedFinancingOption)) return 0;

  return unmodified
    ? otherData.total_gross_price_unmodified
    : otherData.total_gross_price;
};

export const getSwissTaxRebateSubsidy = (
  price: number,
  isStandaloneBattery = false,
  selectedFinancingOption: Cloud$PurchaseModelCode = purchaseModelCode.BUY_NOW,
) => {
  if (
    isStandaloneBattery ||
    selectedFinancingOption === purchaseModelCode.LEASING
  )
    return 0;
  const TAX_REBATE_PERCENTAGE = 20;
  return (price / 100) * TAX_REBATE_PERCENTAGE;
};

export const getPackageGrossPrice = (
  selectedFinancingOption: Cloud$FinancingOption,
): number => {
  const selectedPurchaseModelCode = selectedFinancingOption.purchase_model_code;
  const {
    total_gross_price: totalGrossPrice,
    total_gross_price_unmodified: totalGrossPriceUnmodified,
  } = selectedFinancingOption;

  switch (selectedPurchaseModelCode) {
    case purchaseModelCode.LOAN:
      return selectedFinancingOption.monthly_loan_gross_price;
    case purchaseModelCode.LEASING:
      return selectedFinancingOption.monthly_leasing_gross_price;

    default:
      // If we have a fixed price discount that increases the total gross price,
      // we do not want to show the lower pre-discount unmodified price.
      // Else, for normal discounts, we show the higher pre-discount unmodified price,
      // to make it clear that the customer is getting a discount.
      return Math.max(totalGrossPrice, totalGrossPriceUnmodified);
  }
};

export const getPackagePrice = (
  selectedFinancingOption: Cloud$FinancingOption,
  config: Otovo$Config,
  subsidyType?: Cloud$SubsidyType,
): number => {
  const showNetPrice =
    config.pricing.calcPageSubsidyDisplay === subsidyDisplayEnum.SUBTRACT;

  if (selectedFinancingOption.purchase_model_code === purchaseModelCode.LOAN) {
    return showNetPrice
      ? selectedFinancingOption.monthly_loan_net_price
      : selectedFinancingOption.monthly_loan_gross_price;
  }

  if (
    selectedFinancingOption.purchase_model_code === purchaseModelCode.LEASING
  ) {
    return shouldSubtractSubsidyFromLeasingPrice(subsidyType)
      ? selectedFinancingOption.monthly_leasing_net_price
      : selectedFinancingOption.monthly_leasing_gross_price;
  }

  return showNetPrice
    ? selectedFinancingOption.total_net_price
    : selectedFinancingOption.total_gross_price;
};

export const getTotalBuyNowPrice = (
  selectedFinancingOption: Cloud$FinancingOption,
  config: Otovo$Config,
): number => {
  const showNetPrice =
    config.pricing.calcPageSubsidyDisplay === subsidyDisplayEnum.SUBTRACT;

  if (showNetPrice) {
    return selectedFinancingOption.total_net_price;
  } else {
    return selectedFinancingOption.total_gross_price;
  }
};

export const getFirstMonthlyPrice = (
  selectedFinancingOption: Cloud$FinancingOption,
  config: Otovo$Config,
  subsidyType?: Cloud$SubsidyType,
): number => {
  const EvChargerPriceGrossPrice = getEvChargerGrossPrice(
    selectedFinancingOption,
  );
  const otherNodePrice = getOtherGrossPrice(selectedFinancingOption);
  const packagePrice = getPackagePrice(
    selectedFinancingOption,
    config,
    subsidyType,
  );
  return packagePrice + EvChargerPriceGrossPrice + otherNodePrice;
};

export const getPerUnit = (
  selectedFinancingOption: Cloud$FinancingOption,
): PerUnitType => {
  if (
    selectedFinancingOption.purchase_model_code === purchaseModelCode.LEASING ||
    selectedFinancingOption.purchase_model_code === purchaseModelCode.LOAN
  ) {
    return 'month';
  }

  return '';
};
```



I understand you want to extract the subsidy calculation logic to make it more reusable. Here's how we can decompose this:

```typescript
export const shouldSubtractSubsidy = (
  purchaseModelCode: Cloud$PurchaseModelCode,
  config: Otovo$Config,
  subsidyType?: Cloud$SubsidyType
): boolean => {
  // For regular purchases
  if (purchaseModelCode !== purchaseModelCode.LEASING) {
    return config.pricing.calcPageSubsidyDisplay === subsidyDisplayEnum.SUBTRACT;
  }

  // For leasing
  return shouldSubtractSubsidyFromLeasingPrice(subsidyType);
};

export const getPriceWithSubsidy = (
  finOption: Cloud$FinancingOption,
  config: Otovo$Config,
  subsidyType?: Cloud$SubsidyType
): number => {
  const subtractSubsidy = shouldSubtractSubsidy(
    finOption.purchase_model_code,
    config,
    subsidyType
  );

  if (finOption.purchase_model_code === purchaseModelCode.LOAN) {
    return subtractSubsidy
      ? finOption.monthly_loan_net_price
      : finOption.monthly_loan_gross_price;
  }

  if (finOption.purchase_model_code === purchaseModelCode.LEASING) {
    return subtractSubsidy
      ? finOption.monthly_leasing_net_price
      : finOption.monthly_leasing_gross_price;
  }

  return subtractSubsidy
    ? finOption.total_net_price
    : finOption.total_gross_price;
};
```

Then you can refactor `getPackagePrice` to use this:

```typescript
export const getPackagePrice = (
  selectedFinancingOption: Cloud$FinancingOption,
  config: Otovo$Config,
  subsidyType?: Cloud$SubsidyType
): number => {
  return getPriceWithSubsidy(selectedFinancingOption, config, subsidyType);
};
```

This gives you several benefits:
1. The subsidy logic is now in one place (`shouldSubtractSubsidy`)
2. You can use `getPriceWithSubsidy` anywhere you need to apply the same subsidy rules
3. `getTotalBuyNowPrice` could also be simplified to use this same logic
4. If the subsidy rules change, you only need to update one place

You could then simplify `getTotalBuyNowPrice` to:

```typescript
export const getTotalBuyNowPrice = (
  selectedFinancingOption: Cloud$FinancingOption,
  config: Otovo$Config
): number => {
  return getPriceWithSubsidy(selectedFinancingOption, config);
};
```

This ensures consistent handling of subsidies across all price calculations and makes the code more maintainable.
actually, I think it's easier to just add an additional argument that will never subtract subsidy. let's call it subsidyStrategy: which will be of type string and we'll compare that with subsidydisplayenum. that way we can call this function two times and look at the difference to decide.
Ah yes, that's a cleaner approach! Here's how we can modify `getPackagePrice`:

```typescript
export const getPackagePrice = (
  selectedFinancingOption: Cloud$FinancingOption,
  config: Otovo$Config,
  subsidyType?: Cloud$SubsidyType,
  subsidyStrategy?: keyof typeof subsidyDisplayEnum
): number => {
  const showNetPrice =
    subsidyStrategy ?? config.pricing.calcPageSubsidyDisplay === subsidyDisplayEnum.SUBTRACT;

  if (selectedFinancingOption.purchase_model_code === purchaseModelCode.LOAN) {
    return showNetPrice
      ? selectedFinancingOption.monthly_loan_net_price
      : selectedFinancingOption.monthly_loan_gross_price;
  }

  if (selectedFinancingOption.purchase_model_code === purchaseModelCode.LEASING) {
    return shouldSubtractSubsidyFromLeasingPrice(subsidyType)
      ? selectedFinancingOption.monthly_leasing_net_price
      : selectedFinancingOption.monthly_leasing_gross_price;
  }

  return showNetPrice
    ? selectedFinancingOption.total_net_price
    : selectedFinancingOption.total_gross_price;
};
```

Now you can call it like:
```typescript
const priceWithSubsidy = getPackagePrice(finOption, config, subsidyType);
const priceWithoutSubsidy = getPackagePrice(finOption, config, subsidyType, subsidyDisplayEnum.ADD);
const subsidyAmount = priceWithoutSubsidy - priceWithSubsidy;
```

This way you can easily calculate the subsidy amount by comparing the two prices!
why the ?? operator?

You're right, the `??` (nullish coalescing) operator isn't what we want here. We want to use the explicitly passed `subsidyStrategy` if it exists, or fall back to the config check. Here's the corrected version:

```typescript
export const getPackagePrice = (
  selectedFinancingOption: Cloud$FinancingOption,
  config: Otovo$Config,
  subsidyType?: Cloud$SubsidyType,
  subsidyStrategy?: keyof typeof subsidyDisplayEnum
): number => {
  const showNetPrice = subsidyStrategy 
    ? subsidyStrategy === subsidyDisplayEnum.SUBTRACT
    : config.pricing.calcPageSubsidyDisplay === subsidyDisplayEnum.SUBTRACT;

  // ... rest of the function
};
```

The `??` operator would only fall back to the right side if the left side was `null` or `undefined`, but here we want to use the `subsidyStrategy` parameter whenever it's provided, regardless of its value. This ternary expression better expresses that logic.
how do I get the valueof instead of keyof?
To get the values of the enum instead of the keys, you can use `typeof subsidyDisplayEnum[keyof typeof subsidyDisplayEnum]`. Here's how to fix the type:

```typescript
export const getPackagePrice = (
  selectedFinancingOption: Cloud$FinancingOption,
  config: Otovo$Config,
  subsidyType?: Cloud$SubsidyType,
  subsidyStrategy?: typeof subsidyDisplayEnum[keyof typeof subsidyDisplayEnum]
): number => {
  const showNetPrice = subsidyStrategy 
    ? subsidyStrategy === subsidyDisplayEnum.SUBTRACT
    : config.pricing.calcPageSubsidyDisplay === subsidyDisplayEnum.SUBTRACT;

  // ... rest of the function
};
```

Now `subsidyStrategy` will accept the actual enum values rather than the keys. If `subsidyDisplayEnum` is something like:
```typescript
export const subsidyDisplayEnum = {
  SUBTRACT: 'subtract',
  ADD: 'add',
} as const;
```
Then `subsidyStrategy` will accept `'subtract'` or `'add'` rather than `'SUBTRACT'` or `'ADD'`.
